Script: 0-alias
#!/bin/bash
alias ls='rm *'

Explanation:
First line: #!/bin/bash - Shebang specifying Bash interpreter

Second line: alias ls='rm *' - Creates an alias where typing ls will execute rm *

What happens when you run this:
After sourcing the script with source ./0-alias, the alias becomes active

When you type ls, it actually runs rm * which deletes all files in the current directory

To temporarily disable the alias and use the real ls command, you prefix with backslash: \ls

Demonstration (as shown in the example):
julien@ubuntu:/tmp/0x03$ ls
0-alias  file1  file2
julien@ubuntu:/tmp/0x03$ source ./0-alias 
julien@ubuntu:/tmp/0x03$ ls
# All files get deleted by 'rm *'
julien@ubuntu:/tmp/0x03$ \ls
# Shows the actual ls output (but no files remain after the alias ran)

Note: This is a dangerous alias for demonstration purposes only. In real scenarios, you'd want safer aliases like alias ls='ls --color=auto' or alias rm='rm -i'.

